<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The first author, Mrs Hsueh Lee, and Mr Hou-Jay Chen found young larvae feeding on tender shoots (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Field photographs of Pyrrhalta houjayi sp. nov. on host plant A young larvae feeding on tender shoots B host plant blooming and sprouting at the same time in Tahsuehshan (大雪山) C flower buds with holes caused by larvae D Larva found inside the flower buds E one larva feeding on pedicels F adults." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545539" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">9A</figureCitation>
) April 1, 2009 in Lalashan, northern Taiwan. mature larvae started to burrow into soil and built underground chambers for pupation April 11. The newly eclosed adults emerged from soil April 28. The first author and Mr. Ta-Hsiang Lee found the host plants blooming and sprouting at the same time (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Field photographs of Pyrrhalta houjayi sp. nov. on host plant A young larvae feeding on tender shoots B host plant blooming and sprouting at the same time in Tahsuehshan (大雪山) C flower buds with holes caused by larvae D Larva found inside the flower buds E one larva feeding on pedicels F adults." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545539" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">9B</figureCitation>
) April 21, 2010 in Tahsuehshan, central Taiwan. Many larvae were found inside flower buds with holes (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Field photographs of Pyrrhalta houjayi sp. nov. on host plant A young larvae feeding on tender shoots B host plant blooming and sprouting at the same time in Tahsuehshan (大雪山) C flower buds with holes caused by larvae D Larva found inside the flower buds E one larva feeding on pedicels F adults." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545539" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">9C, D</figureCitation>
). Some larvae preferred to feed on pedicels (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Field photographs of Pyrrhalta houjayi sp. nov. on host plant A young larvae feeding on tender shoots B host plant blooming and sprouting at the same time in Tahsuehshan (大雪山) C flower buds with holes caused by larvae D Larva found inside the flower buds E one larva feeding on pedicels F adults." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545539" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">9E</figureCitation>
). Newly emerged adults appeared during late spring, into summer (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Field photographs of Pyrrhalta houjayi sp. nov. on host plant A young larvae feeding on tender shoots B host plant blooming and sprouting at the same time in Tahsuehshan (大雪山) C flower buds with holes caused by larvae D Larva found inside the flower buds E one larva feeding on pedicels F adults." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545539" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">9F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
